{
  "analysis": "You are in a root shell inside the container (/app). There is currently no information about any MySQL server or databases. Nothing has been attempted yet to connect to MySQL from this shell. To proceed I need to inspect the MySQL server (if present) and see available databases/tables so I can answer your future SQL question. I will try to connect to the local MySQL client and list databases. If the mysql client isn't available or authentication fails, I'll report that output so we can adapt.",
  "plan": "Attempt to run a non-interactive MySQL client command to list databases. This will tell us whether MySQL client is installed and whether we can connect to a local server as root without a password. If successful, we'll see available databases and decide the next SQL to run based on your question. Command: run mysql with -e 'SHOW DATABASES;' so it returns quickly in the terminal.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "mysql --batch --skip-column-names -e 'SHOW DATABASES;'\n",
      "duration": 2.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The mysql client is not installed in the container (mysql: command not found). No MySQL server or databases have been inspected yet. To run SQL against a MySQL server we need a client. Next step is to install a MySQL client (or MariaDB client) so we can connect to any available server. If there's no network or package manager, we'll see the failure output and adapt. After installing a client, we'll attempt to connect or list servers/databases as requested.",
  "plan": "1) Update package lists with apt-get update so we can install packages. 2) Install a MySQL client package (default-mysql-client). 3) If installation succeeds, try listing databases with the mysql client: mysql --batch --skip-column-names -e 'SHOW DATABASES;'.\n\nI expect apt-get update to fetch package metadata, apt-get install to install the client, and then the mysql command to either list databases (if a server is available and allows connection) or report connection/authentication errors which we will handle next.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "apt-get update\n",
      "duration": 8.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "apt-get install -y default-mysql-client\n",
      "duration": 20.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "The mysql client has just been installed successfully in the container. No connection attempts to a MySQL server have been made yet. The next step is to try to connect to a local MySQL server (or the default socket) and list available databases. If there's no server running or socket access is denied, the mysql client will report an error and we'll adapt (for example by checking for running mysqld processes, looking for configuration, or asking you for connection credentials/host).",
  "plan": "Run the mysql client to issue a simple non-interactive statement that lists databases: SHOW DATABASES;. This will reveal whether a local MySQL server is running and accessible and what databases exist. Depending on the output, we'll either proceed to query a specific database/table you ask about, or troubleshoot connection availability (check mysqld process and sockets or ask for host/credentials).",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "mysql --batch --skip-column-names -e 'SHOW DATABASES;'\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}
